    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-07-17T11:20:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-07-17T11:20:00-05:00" n="50"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d50">
                <head>50. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Libya</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d50fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss
                            target="#t_PET1">PET</gloss> 14 LIBYA. Secret; <gloss
                            target="#t_Limdis1">Limdis</gloss>. Drafted on September 16 by <persName
                            corresp="#p_CW1">Clark</persName> (<gloss target="#t_E1"
                            >E</gloss>/ORF/<gloss target="#t_FSE1">FSE</gloss>) and <persName
                            corresp="#p_BJ1">Blake</persName> (<gloss target="#t_AFN1"
                        >AF/N</gloss>); cleared in <gloss target="#t_E1">E</gloss>/ORF/<gloss
                            target="#t_FSE1">FSE</gloss>; and approved by <persName corresp="#p_BJ1"
                            >Blake</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-07-17T16:20:00+00:00">July 17, 1970, 1620Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>114592. <gloss target="#t_Ref1">Ref</gloss>: Tripoli 1641.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d50fn2">In telegram 1641 from Tripoli, July 14, the Embassy provided
                        information concerning the ongoing negotiations between Libya and Marathon.
                        (Ibid., <gloss target="#t_PET1">PET</gloss> 15–2 LIBYA)</note> Subject:
                        <gloss target="#t_Postedprice1">Posted Price</gloss> Negotiations.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Dept has consistently take position vis-à-vis all oil companies involved
                        in Libyan problem that decisions regarding offers in <gloss
                            target="#t_Postedprice1">posted price</gloss>
                        <pb facs="0154" n="116" xml:id="pg_116"/>negotiations was matter for each
                        company to decide for itself in terms its own best interests, taking into
                        account its particular position in Libya and its interests elsewhere.
                        Position of <gloss target="#t_Independents1">independent</gloss> oil
                        companies such as Occidental for example is very different in Libya and
                        world-wide than that of major integrated international company such as
                            <gloss target="#t_Esso1">Esso</gloss>. If asked by any oil company we
                        plan to maintain this position and we assume Embassy will also.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>We note that argument for accepting forced <gloss target="#t_Postedprice1"
                            >posted price</gloss> increase in Libya under protest as means of
                        avoiding pressure to increase <gloss target="#t_Postedprice1">posted
                            price</gloss> in Persian Gulf of course only applies to <gloss
                            target="#t_Majors1">majors</gloss> (<gloss target="#t_Esso1"
                            >Esso</gloss>, Amoseas Group, and <gloss target="#t_Mobil1"
                            >Mobil</gloss>). A substantial de facto <gloss target="#t_Postedprice1"
                            >posted price</gloss> increase in Libya would no doubt be followed by
                        pressure to increase <gloss target="#t_Postedprice1">posted price</gloss> in
                        Persian Gulf in any event. <gloss target="#t_Independents1"
                            >Independents</gloss> such as Oasis Group members might have more to
                        gain by flexibility now since a negotiated <gloss target="#t_Postedprice1"
                            >posted price</gloss>, whatever it might be, could be less or with less
                        onerous conditions attached than a price established by fiat. To suggest
                            <gloss target="#t_Independents1">independents</gloss> not be forthcoming
                        now in negotiations would appear less in their interest and more in the
                        interest of the <gloss target="#t_Majors1">majors</gloss>, and <gloss
                            target="#t_Independents1">independents</gloss> might later blame <gloss
                            target="#t_USG1">USG</gloss> if events turn out badly.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>We are concerned by what appears to be emerging “Iraq mentality” on the
                        part of <gloss target="#t_Majors1">majors</gloss> (Tripoli 1557, para
                            7),<note n="3" xml:id="d50fn3">Dated July 2. (Ibid., <gloss
                                target="#t_PET1">PET</gloss> 6 LIBYA)</note> namely to give in on
                        issues only when forced, to disinvest, to keep others out of their
                        concession areas as long as possible, and to maximize profits soonest. Such
                        an attitude may not appeal to <gloss target="#t_Independents1"
                            >independents</gloss> without production outside Libya such as Marathon,
                        who have a greater incentive to remain in Libya for as long as
                        possible.</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">End</hi>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rogers</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
